"Simolo C., Brunetti M., Maugeri M., Nanni T.","Evolution of extreme temperatures in a warming climate",2011,"Geophysical Research Letters","38","16", L16701,"","",,,10.1029/2011GL048437,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80051726677&partnerID=40&md5=4f764205574c12382ad87398a8bbb5bb","Institute of Atmospheric Sciences and Climate, National Research Council (ISAC-CNR), Via Gobetti 101, I-40129 Bologna, Italy; Dipartimento di Fisica, Universit Degli Studi di Milano, Via Celoria 16, I-20133 Milano, Italy","Simolo, C., Institute of Atmospheric Sciences and Climate, National Research Council (ISAC-CNR), Via Gobetti 101, I-40129 Bologna, Italy; Brunetti, M., Institute of Atmospheric Sciences and Climate, National Research Council (ISAC-CNR), Via Gobetti 101, I-40129 Bologna, Italy; Maugeri, M., Institute of Atmospheric Sciences and Climate, National Research Council (ISAC-CNR), Via Gobetti 101, I-40129 Bologna, Italy, Dipartimento di Fisica, Universit Degli Studi di Milano, Via Celoria 16, I-20133 Milano, Italy; Nanni, T., Institute of Atmospheric Sciences and Climate, National Research Council (ISAC-CNR), Via Gobetti 101, I-40129 Bologna, Italy","The ongoing increase in extremely warm temperature events across large areas of the globe is generally thought to be a signature of a more extreme climate. However, it is still unclear whether global warming is accompanied by changes in statistical properties beyond the mean, such as an increasing temperature variability. Here we shed light on this issue by uncovering the way probabilities of extremes are being influenced by temperature evolution. Focusing on Europe, we show how the behavior of warm and cold extremes can be determined to a high accuracy by statistically modeling daily temperatures and their changes. Detailed comparison with observations over the past decades puts forward the dominant role of the mean in explaining exceptionally hot events, and rules out contributions from potential changes in second and higher moments. Copyright 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Daily temperatures; Extreme temperatures; Higher moments; Potential change; Statistical properties; Temperature evolution; Temperature variability; Warm temperatures; Warming climate; Global warming; accuracy assessment; diurnal variation; global warming; probability; regional climate; temperature effect; Europe",,,,,,"Alexander, L.V., Global observed changes in daily climate extremes of temperature and precipitation (2006) J. Geophys. Res., 111, pp. D05109. , doi:10.1029/2005JD006290; Azzalini, A., The skew-normal distribution and related multivariate families (2005) Scand. J. Stat., 32, p. 159; Ballester, J., Giorgi, F., Rodò, X., Changes in European temperature extremes can be predicted from changes in PDF central statistics (2010) Clim. Change, 98, p. 277; Christidis, N., Stott, P.A., Brown, S., Hegerl, G.C., Caesar, J., Detection of changes in temperature extremes during the second half of the 20th century (2005) Geophysical Research Letters, 32 (20), pp. 1-4. , DOI 10.1029/2005GL023885, L20716; Clark, R.T., Brown, S.J., Murphy, J.M., Modeling northern hemisphere summer heat extreme changes and their uncertainties using a physics ensemble of climate sensitivity experiments (2006) J. Clim., 19, p. 4418; Della-Marta, P.M., Haylock, M.R., Luterbacher, J., Wanner, H., Doubled length of western European summer heat waves since 1880 (2007) Journal of Geophysical Research D: Atmospheres, 112 (15), pp. D15103. , DOI 10.1029/2007JD008510; Fischer, E.M., Schär, C., Future changes in daily summer temperature variability: Driving processes and role for temperature extremes (2009) Clim. Dyn., 33, p. 917; Giorgi, F., Climate change hot-spots (2006) Geophysical Research Letters, 33 (8), pp. L08707. , DOI 10.1029/2006GL025734; Hirschi, M., Observational evidence for soil-moisture impact on hot extremes in southeastern Europe (2011) Nat. Geosci., 4, p. 17; Hosking, J.R.M., L-moments: Analysis and esti